description: A Bed n' Breakfast situated just 12 minutes from Downtown Nashville, in beautiful Bells Bend, Tennessee. Whooping Crane Farm-Stay accomodates 1 to 6 guests, with it's 3 bedrooms and 1.5 baths. The home over-looks 120 spacious acres above the Cumberland River. A working farm which focuses on American Milking Devon Cattle, biodynamic vegetable growing and a 2 acre peach, blackberry + apple orchard. Local farm tours, square dances and  beautiful views. Built in the late 1800s as two separate "dog run" style homes, combined into one in the early 1940s. Fireplaces abundant, clean style with nods to it's farmhouse history, newly renovated kitchen, smoke house and argentine asado grill for the culinarily curious. You'll have access to the farm's immediate property (about 20 acres). We also have quick access to both Bells Bend Park and Beaman Park for hiking. Breakfast, pastries from local bakers, snacks and/or lunch picnics are available to guests each day of their stay. The host doesn't live
name: Whooping Crane Farm, 12 min. from Nashville

description: This 2BR/1BA apartment is part of McMillin Court, a ‘50s motel-turned-vacation-rental complex steeped in Nashville history and owned by one of the city’s BBQ legends. Walk next door to try his famous recipes! Stay in a 2BR/1BA apartment at a 1950s-inspired retro motel with as much personality as its owner, Nashville BBQ legend Jack Cawthon. Walk next door to Jack’s Bar-B-Que and try the best brisket and ribs in the city!   HISTORY   The story starts in 1831, when this site in Capitol Hill was home to the Tennessee State Penitentiary. The jail was moved in 1898, and the Governor divided the property. Over a hundred years later in 2013, Jack restored a corner of this 10-acre stretch and opened his third restaurant, Jack’s Bar-B-Que – now a Nashville landmark.     Since then, Jack acquired the land behind Jack’s Bar-B-Que and created McMillin Court, a 1950’s-inspired, 15-unit motel where you can gather with a group of nearly any size. Each unit at McMillin Court sleeps 6 people, with room
name: Landmark McMillin Court Apartment

description: Germantown's newest Airbnb! The original 1800’s cottage has been restored offering amenities we enjoy today while keeping the historic character. Branan White has mastered the art of combining 18th and 19th Century French and English antiques with repurposed and recycled industrial pieces.  The finished result is a home you adore and want to call “home”. Enter 1309 through the picket fence gate and the walk takes you to the front gathering porch. description: This beautiful one bedroom Carriage House is registered with the National Register of Historic Places. Built in 1870, this loft apartment features exposed brick walls, vaulted ceilings, an outdoor urban garden and 1,500sqft of open space. One of Nashville's two last-standing carriage homes, our Carriage House originally served as the stables, paddock, tack room and servants' quarters for George Henry Ratterman (owner of the “big house" out front). If you use your imagination, you can still see where carriages would enter!  The former tack room sat on the lower right side of the property, and the stable was on the left. Upstairs, where this apartment is located, housed the servants. The property was condemned and scheduled for demolition by the city in 1979 before it was purchased and restored by the current property owner. Beginning in 1979, The Carriage House was used as a storage for a number of renovations happening around Germantown during the modern-day renaissance of the neighbor
name: 1840's Downtown Carriage House

description: This cozy one bedroom apt has everything you need, including a view that overlooks Midtown's best! Looking out the window you'll see Winners Bar, Losers Bar, Rebar, Soulshine, Slider House and more! Within the block, dine at Hattie B's, Tavern, Noshville, Chuy's, Broadway Brewhouse and Union Common! One of the only places to rent in the historical Midtown neighborhood! I mean, JOHNNY CASH lived in this building when he was a young'n! Waylon Jennings also lived here and Kris Kristofferson called it home when he was a young buck too! It is deemed a historical landmark which is why there haven't been any major renovations. It was built in 1910 and hasn't been renovated since the 40's. It is a little old and beat up. If you like Hilton's and the Ritz's of the world, this place isn't for you. But if you want to be in the heart of Midtown where all of the music industry hangs, and spend time in the same building of legendary artists and songwriters, this is your spot! As much as needed! Bus.
name: Heart of Midtown! Music City!

description: This 2BR/1BA apartment is part of McMillin Court, a ‘50s motel-turned-vacation-rental complex steeped in Nashville history and owned by one of the city’s BBQ legends. Walk next door to try his famous recipes! Stay in a 2BR/1BA apartment at a 1950s-inspired retro motel with as much personality as its owner, Nashville BBQ legend Jack Cawthon. Walk next door to Jack’s Bar-B-Que and try the best brisket and ribs in the city!   HISTORY   The story starts in 1831, when this site in Capitol Hill was home to the Tennessee State Penitentiary. The jail was moved in 1898, and the Governor divided the property. Over a hundred years later in 2013, Jack restored a corner of this 10-acre stretch and opened his third restaurant, Jack’s Bar-B-Que – now a Nashville landmark.     Since then, Jack acquired the land behind Jack’s Bar-B-Que and created McMillin Court, a 1950’s-inspired, 15-unit motel where you can gather with a group of nearly any size. name: Landmark McMillin Court Apartment

What exactly are tiny houses? Simply put they are a social movement where people are downsizing the space that they live in. The typical American home is around 2600 square feet, while the typical small or tiny house is around 100-400 square feet. Tiny Houses come in all shapes, sizes and forms but they focus on smaller spaces and simplified living. description: Beautiful spacious cottage is ideal for a romantic getaway or city retreat! Under 16 minutes away from downtown Nashville, yet the proximity to nature and privacy will make you feel like you are a world away! Recently renovated White Creek retreat. This beautifully appointed cottage is just under 900 square feet of indoor living space, with a two sided wrap around covered porch overlook a beautiful creek! Two bedrooms with queen size beds make it a great cozy get away for a couple, or comfortably able to fit 4.  The kitchen is spacious, with full size fridge and 4 range stove/oven, and has the supplies you need to make your stay fulfilling. Washer and dryer available. You have the entire cottage to yourself, with own parking area and secluded creekside. We are typically nearby but wont likely be stopping by unless requested. Whites Creek is a beautiful historic neighborhood. In the backyard of the cottage, the infamous Jesse James escaped after robbing the Whites Creek Bank and Trust!

description: Permitted with Metro Nashville. Complies with safety inspections and insurance. The following city/state taxes are now mandated: Sales 9.25%, Hotel 6% on the taxable portion plus $2.50 per night and are NOT INCLUDED in the stated base rate.
